Detailed Description

Complex numbers class.

The class Complex provides all elementary operations on complex numbers. All the operators +, -, *, /, ==, != are defined in the canonical way. Additional complex trigonometric functions such as Complex.Cosine, ... are also provided. Note that the Complex structures has two special constant values Complex.NaN and Complex.Infinity.

In order to avoid possible ambiguities resulting from a Complex(double, double) constructor, the static methods Complex.FromRealImaginary and Complex.FromModulusArgument are provided instead.

        Complex x = Complex.FromRealImaginary(1d, 2d);
        Complex y = Complex.FromModulusArgument(1d, Math.Pi);
        Complex z = (x + y) / (x - y);

Since there is no canonical order among the complex numbers, Complex does not implement IComparable but several lexicographic IComparer implementations are provided, see Complex.RealImaginaryComparer, Complex.ModulusArgumentComparer and Complex.ArgumentModulusComparer.

For mathematical details about complex numbers, please have a look at the Wikipedia

Definition at line 686 of file Complex.cs.

static Complex MathNet.Numerics.Complex.Parse ( string  complex  )  [static]

Parse a string into a Complex.

The adopted string representation for the complex numbers is UVW+I*XYZ where UVW and XYZ are double strings. Some alternative representations are UVW+XYZi, UVW+iXYZ, UVW and iXYZ. Additionally the string "NaN" is mapped to Complex.NaN, the string "Infinity" to Complex.ComplexInfinity, "PositiveInfinity" to Complex.DirectedInfinity(Complex.One), "NegativeInfinity" to Complex.DirectedInfinity(-Complex.One) and finally "DirectedInfinity(WVW+I*XYZ)" to Complex.DirectedInfinity(WVW+I*XYZ). 

            Complex z = Complex.Parse("12.5+I*7");
            Complex nan = Complex.Parse("NaN");
            Complex infinity = Complex.Parse("Infinity");

This method is symmetric to Complex.ToString().

double MathNet::Numerics.Complex::Argument [get, set]

Gets or sets the argument of this Complex.

Argument always returns a value bigger than negative Pi and smaller or equal to Pi. If this Complex is zero, the Complex is assumed to be positive real with an argument of zero.

Definition at line 136 of file Complex.cs.

Complex MathNet::Numerics.Complex::Conjugate [get, set]

Gets or sets the conjugate of this Complex.

The semantic of setting the conjugate is such that 

            // a, b of type Complex
            a.Conjugate = b;

is equivalent to 

            // a, b of type Complex
            a = b.Conjugate

static Complex MathNet::Numerics.Complex::Infinity [static, get]

Represents the infinity value. This field is constant.

The semantic associated to this value is a Complex of infinite real and imaginary part. If you need more formal complex number handling (according to the Riemann Sphere and the extended complex plane C*, or using directed infinity) please check out the alternative MathNet.PreciseNumerics and MathNet.Symbolics packages instead.
